e and surprising challenges and opportunities arise when city borders are crossed, voices meet, and artistic traditions find their counterparts. Using the Latin word for "translation," translatio, or "to carry across," as a point of departure, Avenues of Translation explores how translation perpetuates, diversifies, deepens, and expands the literary production of cities in their greater cultural context, and how translation shapes an understanding of and access to a city's past and present literary and cultural practices. Thinking about translation and the city is a way to tell the backstories of the cities, texts, and authors that are united by acts of translation. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpreting. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Esther.1 aBorinsky, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorinsky, Alicia.1 aBush, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBush, Peter.1 aCifuentes-Goodbody, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuprey, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuprey, Jennifer.1 aGalasso, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalasso, Regina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGalasso, Regina.1 aGoodbody, Nicholas Cifuentes.1 aHatfield, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatfield, Charles.1 aHazelton, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo